[normal]Written evidence submitted by The[bold] Royal [bold]Academy of Engineering (WSC095)[bold]Founded in 1976, The Royal Academy of Engineering promotes the engineering and technological welfare of the country. Our fellowship – comprising the UK’s most eminent engineers – 
[normal]provides the leadership and expertise for our activities, which focus on the relationships between engineering, technology, and the quality of life. As a national academy, we provide independent and impartial advice to Government; work to secure the next g
[normal]eneration of engineers; and provide a voice for Britain’s engineering community.
[normal]Why do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]When women leave academia, what 
[normal]careers do they transition into? What are the consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?
[normal]What should universities and th
[normal]e higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?
[normal]What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers? 
